ftpd.library/--background--                       ftpd.library/--background--

	I was writing my ftp server and came accross a number of problems, this
	is hopefully the best way for me to solve them. Among other things it is
	intended for it to be able to handle as many connections as the system
	is able to take, unlike the current limit of around 64 per process.

	The library also implements ways for the connections to be snooped, and an
	overall picture of the connections to be seen, without hard-coding any GUI
	engine into the server.


ftpd.library/LoadPrefs                                 ftpd.library/LoadPrefs
  NAME
	LoadPrefs - Load the prefs for the server.

  SYNOPSIS
	success = LoadPrefs( prefsname );
	                        A0

	BOOL LoadPrefs( char *prefsname );

  FUNCTION
	This will load the specified prefs file. Note that the prefs only deal
	with user/access, the daemon process(es) must reside in InetD, and they
	specify the ports used.


ftpd.library/ObtainFTPd                               ftpd.library/ObtainFTPd
  NAME
	ObtainFTPd - Create a new ftp server.

  SYNOPSIS
	ObtainFTPd( id );
	            D0

	void ObtainFTPd( long id );

  FUNCTION
	Pass this the result of ReleaseSocket() and it will take over full running
	of the socket to act as the FTP server. If there are no servers free then
	it will spawn a new one. There are a maximum of 32 connections per server,
	and it will automatically quit any server that has none (if specified by
	the settings).

	Each server goes under the name "ftpd_server" and handles both control and
	data sockets.

  SIGNALS
	CTRL_C - Close *all* servers and all connections.
	CTRL_D - Close this server and all its connections.
	CTRL_E - Close this server and pass all connections to another.
	CTRL_F - Close all data connections on this server.




ftpd.library/AbortFTP                                   ftpd.library/AbortFTP
  NAME
	AbortFTP - abort any xfer in progress.

  SYNOPSIS
	AbortFTP( ftp );
	          A0

	void AbortFTP( struct FTPData *ftp );

  FUNCTION
	This function closes and cleans up any file transfers currently in progress
	by this connection.

  INPUTS
	ftp - connection to remove file transfers from


ftpd.library/AddEventHook                             ftpd.library/AddEventHook
  NAME
	AddEventHook - add an event monitoring hook.

  SYNOPSIS
	return = AddEventHook( hook, taglist );
	  D0                    A0     A1

	ULONG AddEventHook( struct Hook *hook, struct TagItem *taglist );

  FUNCTION
	This function lets you add a hook to monitor all events that happen. These
	can be general events (Open/Close), ftp events, file events, or even
	specific commands.

	'hook' is a standard Amiga callback hook. The hook will be called with a
	struct FTPData in A2 (if this is in relation to a connection), and the
	type of event that triggered it in A1. Do not assume the contents of A2.

	'taglist' is a pointer to a list of TagItems. Currently defined tags are
	(contents of A2 in brackets) -
	FTP_EVENT_OPEN (NULL)
	 Server opened. will be called on start if the server is open by default.
	 Result ignored.
	FTP_EVENT_CLOSE (NULL)
	 Server closed, will be called on quit if the server is still open.
	 Result ignored.
	FTP_EVENT_ACCEPT (struct FTPData *)
	 Accepting a control connection. Result is TRUE/FALSE, Accept/Deny.
	 Note: on Deny no message is sent, so best queue some reason.
	FTP_EVENT_SENDFILE (struct FTPData *)
	 Starting to send a file. Result is TRUE/FALSE, Send/Don't.
	FTP_EVENT_SENDFILE2 (struct FTPData *)
	 After a file has been sent. Result is ignored.
	FTP_EVENT_RECVFILE (struct FTPData *)
	 Starting to receive a file. Result is TRUE/FALSE, Receive/Don't.
	FTP_EVENT_RECVFILE2 (struct FTPData *)
	 After receiving a file. Result is ignored.


ftpd.library/AddSnoopHook                             ftpd.library/AddSnoopHook
  NAME
	AddSnoopHook - add an input/output monitoring hook.

  SYNOPSIS
	handle = AddSnoopHook( hook, ftp, userdata, flags );
	  D0                    A0   A1      A2      D0

	struct FTPSnoop *AddSnoopHook( struct Hook *hook, struct FTPData *ftp, APTR userdata, ULONG flags );

  FUNCTION
	This function adds a callback hook to monitor all input/output to an ftp
	control connection. You can add as many hooks as you wish to each
	connection, and every hook is seperate, so in order to watch two seperate
	connections, you need to AddSnoopHook to each.

	'hook' is a standard Amiga callback hook. The hook will be called with
	a struct FTPData in A2 and the text to be sent in a1. If A1 is NULL then
	it has just recieved a line and you can access this from ftp->command and
	ftp->arguments. (You can also use ftp->input, but as this might need
	telnet sequences removed and passwords scrambled this is not advised...)

	'ftp' must be a properly initialised, and connected, FTPData.

	'userdata' is for your own use.

	'flags' are currently unused - but will be in future.

  INPUTS
	hook - callback hook

	ftp - connection to be monitored

	userdata - whatever you want

	flags - currently NULL

  RESULT
	handle - an FTPSnoop handle, or NULL for failure

  NOTE
	If you try to setup a duplicate hook (same Hook and FTPData) then the
	current FTPSnoop will be changed (userdata/flags) and returned again.

	It is advisable NOT to call anything that might block as this is holding
	up the process used for this connection (and probably others).


